            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ramon Vega\u2019s story is one of steady, quiet dedication, a narrative etched into the fog-laced streets connecting Daly City to San Francisco. As the son of Filipino immigrants who settled in Daly City in the 1970s, Ramon was raised on the values of hard work and stability. His father, a mechanic at SFO, and his mother, a nurse at Seton Medical Center, preached the gospel of a practical education and a reliable career\u2014a stark contrast to the dot-com gold rush mentality that would later define the region.\n\nHeeding their advice, Ramon attended San Francisco State University, choosing not a glamorous tech path but a degree in Supply Chain Management. He understood the city's true lifeblood wasn't code, but the tangible goods arriving at its ports and warehouses. He began his career in the bustling logistics hub of Oakland and eventually became an Operations Manager in San Francisco, a master of schedules, shipments, and the unseen choreography that keeps the city stocked and functioning. For over two decades, he has been a steady hand in a volatile economy, his career a quiet testament to his parents\u2019 wisdom.\n\nThe pivotal turning point in Ramon\u2019s life was the loss of his wife, Elena, to cancer twelve years ago. Her passing transformed his meticulous nature from a professional asset into a personal anchor. His routines became a source of comfort: the same 5:30 AM alarm, the strong barako coffee, the 4.5-mile ride on the 38 Geary bus from his quiet Outer Richmond apartment to his SoMa office.\n\nNow 53, Ramon\u2019s life is defined by this rhythm. He is a familiar, friendly face on his morning commute, though he keeps mostly to himself. His social life revolves around Sunday dinners in Daly City with his sister and her children. His hopes are no longer grand; he dreams of a peaceful retirement, of taking a long-overdue trip to the Philippines to see his parents\u2019 home provinces, and of walking along Ocean Beach, feeling the constant, reliable pulse of the tide\u2014a rhythm that mirrors his own contribution to the city he calls home."
